## Why augment a designed experiment with TERN?

A multi-site agricultural trial randomises over treatments at each site, but
not over the soil and water conditions that pre-define how each paddock
responds to those treatments. Two paddocks given the same nitrogen rate can
return very different yields — partly genuine site effect, partly structural
variation in soil texture, water-holding capacity, pH, and antecedent
moisture that the experimental design did not control. **nert** lets you pull
the relevant structural covariates from the **TERN** portal in a single call,
moving them out of "site effect" and into named terms in the model.

This vignette walks through that augmentation on the synthetic `grain`
dataset shipped with the package, comparing three nested models of nitrogen
response: a naive baseline, a moisture-augmented model, and a
full-soil-context model that adds three static SLGA covariates.

## The trial: ten South Australian sites, four nitrogen rates

`grain` is a fabricated multi-site experiment across ten sites in
South Australia: three replicates each, eight wheat varieties, four nitrogen
application rates, and three seeding rates. Each site has its own sowing date
and nitrogen-application date.

```{r grain}
library(nert)
data(grain)
str(grain)
```

```{r sites}
sites <- unique(grain[, c("Site", "Latitude", "Longitude", "NitrogenDate")])
sites
```

## Pulling the TERN covariates with one call

The agronomic story we want to test is straightforward: *the nitrogen
treatment effect is conditional on (i) how much water the soil can hold,
(ii) how much clay is at the surface, (iii) the soil's pH, and (iv) what the
actual soil moisture was during the two weeks immediately after the
fertiliser was surface-applied.* The first three are static SLGA properties;
the fourth is daily SMIPS time-series data.

`collect_tern_data()` retrieves multiple datasets at multiple coordinates in
one call. Static covariates are returned once per location; time-series
covariates are returned once per location-day pair. We pull the three static
SLGA covariates first — one call covers all ten sites:

```{r tern_static}
sites_xy <- data.frame(lon = sites$Longitude, lat = sites$Latitude)

tern_static <- collect_tern_data(
  xy         = sites_xy,
  date_range = "2024-01-01",          # arbitrary — SLGA layers are static
  datasets   = c("AWC", "CLY", "PHC"),
  depth      = "000_005",             # surface 0–5 cm
  verbose    = FALSE
)
tern_static$Site <- sites$Site
tern_static
```

Then daily SMIPS soil moisture index for the 14 days after each site's
nitrogen application — looped per-site so we only fetch dates that matter
for that site:

```{r tern_smips}
smips_per_site <- lapply(seq_len(nrow(sites)), function(i) {
  ndt <- as.Date(sites$NitrogenDate[i])
  d   <- collect_tern_data(
    lon              = sites$Longitude[i],
    lat              = sites$Latitude[i],
    date_range       = seq(ndt, ndt + 14, by = "day"),
    datasets         = "SMIPS",
    smips_collection = "SMindex",
    verbose          = FALSE
  )
  d$Site <- sites$Site[i]
  d
})
smips_data <- do.call(rbind, smips_per_site)
head(smips_data)
```

Per-site summary — the post-fertiliser two-week mean soil moisture index:

```{r smips_avg}
smips_avg <- aggregate(SMIPS_SMindex ~ Site, smips_data, mean)
names(smips_avg)[2] <- "SoilMoisture_avg"
smips_avg
```

Join the four covariates back to `grain`:

```{r join}
grain <- merge(grain, tern_static[, c("Site", "AWC", "CLY", "PHC")], by = "Site")
grain <- merge(grain, smips_avg, by = "Site")
str(grain[, c("Site", "AWC", "CLY", "PHC", "SoilMoisture_avg")])
```

## Three nested models of nitrogen response

We fit a linear mixed-effect model of grain yield, with site and replicate as
random effects, and progressively richer fixed-effect structures.

**Model 1 — naive.** Variety × nitrogen × seed-rate, nothing about soil or
moisture.

```{r model1}
library(nlme)
model1 <- lme(
  fixed  = Yield_Tha ~ Variety * Nitrogen_kgNha * SeedRate_plantsm2,
  random = ~ 1 | Site / Rep,
  data   = grain
)
```

**Model 2 — SMIPS-augmented.** Adds the post-fertiliser soil moisture
average and its interaction with nitrogen rate (anticipating moisture-driven
volatilisation losses).

```{r model2}
model2 <- lme(
  fixed  = Yield_Tha ~ Variety * Nitrogen_kgNha * SeedRate_plantsm2
                      + SoilMoisture_avg
                      + SoilMoisture_avg:Nitrogen_kgNha,
  random = ~ 1 | Site / Rep,
  data   = grain
)
```

**Model 3 — full-context.** Adds the three static SLGA covariates that
pre-determine each paddock's water and nutrient retention.

```{r model3}
model3 <- lme(
  fixed  = Yield_Tha ~ Variety * Nitrogen_kgNha * SeedRate_plantsm2
                      + SoilMoisture_avg
                      + SoilMoisture_avg:Nitrogen_kgNha
                      + AWC + CLY + PHC,
  random = ~ 1 | Site / Rep,
  data   = grain
)
```

Extract the nitrogen-rate effect intervals from each:

```{r intervals}
n_terms <- paste0("Nitrogen_kgNha", c(30, 60, 90))

n_effects <- function(m, label) {
  ints <- intervals(m, which = "fixed")$fixed
  data.frame(ints[n_terms, ], term = n_terms, model = label)
}

ci <- rbind(
  n_effects(model1, "1. naive"),
  n_effects(model2, "2. SMIPS-augmented"),
  n_effects(model3, "3. full-context")
)
ci
```

## Comparing the nitrogen effect

```{r ploteffects}
#| fig.height = 3.4, dpi = 300, out.width = "100%",
#| warning = FALSE, message = FALSE,
#| fig.cap = "Nitrogen effect estimates across three nested models. Each
#|   augmentation tightens the confidence interval by moving structural
#|   variation from the random site effect into named covariates."
library(ggplot2)

pd <- position_dodge(-0.5)
ggplot(ci, aes(x = est., y = term, colour = model)) +
  scale_y_discrete(limits = rev) +
  geom_point(position = pd) +
  geom_errorbarh(aes(xmin = lower, xmax = upper), position = pd, height = 0.2) +
  labs(y = "predictor", x = "estimate", colour = NULL)
```

## What changed and why

Each augmentation tightens the nitrogen effect by moving structural
variation out of the unnamed random site effect and into named covariates:

- **Model 1 → 2**: SMIPS reveals that some paddocks were wetter than others
  in the two weeks after fertiliser was surface-applied; that drives
  volatilisation losses and dilutes the apparent nitrogen response.
- **Model 2 → 3**: AWC, surface clay, and pH explain *why* certain sites
  retain water and nutrients differently in the first place — pre-existing
  structural conditions that the random site effect was previously absorbing.

The full-context model is the most defensible: residual variation is now
genuine experimental error rather than confounded soil and moisture
structure. The same pattern composes for any **nert**-supported variable —
canopy height, evapotranspiration, phenology, soil beta-diversity — and
scales to any number of sites and dates with a single `collect_tern_data()`
call.

## See also

If your analysis crosses multiple Australian data sources rather than only
TERN, **fifo** (`https://codeberg.org/adamhsparks/fifo`) provides a unified
`xy`-based extractor that calls **nert** for TERN, **read.abares** for
ABARES regions and topsoil layers, **weatherOz** for SILO and DPIRD weather,
plus its own GRDC Agroecoregions and DAAS Soil Atlas layers. **nert** stays
the right choice when you need raw TERN rasters or the full set of TERN
variables; **fifo** is the right choice when you want one `xy` query to
return TERN, weather, and tenure data side-by-side.
